			<div class="content" id="post-content-4100066">
									

<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">Minor&nbsp;nitpick,&nbsp;if&nbsp;not&nbsp;already&nbsp;fixed&nbsp;by&nbsp;now.</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">&gt;&gt;&gt;</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<blockquote>
<p>She eats, she sleep, she fights</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Wouldn't it be &quot;sleeps&quot; to match with the &quot;s&quot; of each verb fragment?</p>
<blockquote>
<p>These are people are allowed</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I think its &quot;These people are allowed&#8230;&quot; without the extra are.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>a an easy and cost-effective source of bodies.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Don't believe &quot;a&quot; is necessary.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<br />
Phenomenal piece and I absolutely adore the usage of Kowloon in this sci-fi, dystopian variation on EoD canon. Described in such a way.
<p>There's a loose narration that doesn't need to be confined to a clinical format or preset character. Its like from the mouth of a storyteller as she/he tells about the land and adds little characterizations to it.</p>
<p>Like for example: &quot;Where do the brains come from? Why, mostly from genetically grown clone-stock, of course. No, we can't disclose any information about the process, or our facility.&quot;</p>
<p>Flows freely as we're prefaced with &quot;Imagine&#8230;&quot; at every beginning. First-person narration from the POV of the very company in contrast to the third-person on the enforcer.</p>
<p>I like that you made this doable. Maybe that's just me, but it's definitely hard to do for me. Thank you for this piece. +1.</p>

							</div>

								
